<subSubSection id="65CC001814FBA98A1DC452C426575D3C" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="description">
<paragraph id="88FD8D9E248947EBFE48420D005AE32E" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Description of holotype.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="5D9A12A8DE8FDB4FA652BA5FDAA18593" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
Habitus as in Fig. 
<figureCitation id="3574CFFB5B4D7D92A8DFC10358C40DD2" captionStart="Figures 1–2" captionStartId="F1" captionText="Figures 1 - 2. Geopselaphus bullonorum Hernando &amp; Castro, sp. nov. Habitus in dorsal view 1 male 2 female." figureDoi="10.3897/subtbiol.43.83592.figures1-2" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/673887" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">1</figureCitation>
. Body length: 2.13 mm. Apterous and microphtalmic, with only three omatidia (probably non-functional eyes). Entirely pale brown with lighter maxillary palpi and tarses. Body (specially the head) and appendages (antennae, maxillary palpi and legs) extraordinary elongated and slender. Pubescence of the dorsal surface consist of short suberect white setae on head, pronotum, elytra and abdomen, pubescence on the ventral surface consists of very dense clusters of tomentose setae on the head, mesoventrite and first visible sternite, and short, suberect, white setae on the metaventrite and sternites, other suberect shorter setae on antennae and legs.
</paragraph>
<caption id="A2B96E593548B9F671ADFBB4105F8870" doi="10.3897/subtbiol.43.83592.figures1-2" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/673887" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" start="Figures 1–2" startId="F1">
<paragraph id="999C30A38E9354B8C878BD4451BB8631" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
<emphasis id="2CD64CE28F335377EC57099CA807A642" bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Figures 1-2.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName id="1966325426B306AA8338C6D297C47BFC" authorityName="Hernando &amp; Castro" authorityYear="2022" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Geopselaphus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Geopselaphus bullonorum" order="Coleoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="bullonorum">
<emphasis id="DDA3B0CFF5A427987048421AAC825C77" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Geopselaphus bullonorum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Hernando &amp; Castro, sp. nov. Habitus in dorsal view 
<emphasis id="3320C7F2328A75AAD301BE51933E3024" bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">1</emphasis>
male 
<emphasis id="DD2F5435238665B619A7CB0AB93B7008" bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">2</emphasis>
female.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph id="75EB143062953A6B24C90EC8573C0306" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
<emphasis id="6686DDAA420635FD356862BDC7E198C8" bold="true" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Head</emphasis>
: (Figs 
<figureCitation id="2167248CA68FD827146006B21F0921C2" captionStart="Figures 3–7" captionStartId="F2" captionText="Figures 3 - 7. Geopselaphus bullonorum Hernando &amp; Castro, sp. nov. head 3 dorsal view 4 lateral view. Head appendages 5 A antennae 5 B maxilar palpi. Elytra and abdomen in dorsal view 6 male 7 female." figureDoi="10.3897/subtbiol.43.83592.figures3-7" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/673888" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">3</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation id="25FA9F4AA0606D89263E64526D66BDAE" captionStart="Figures 3–7" captionStartId="F2" captionText="Figures 3 - 7. Geopselaphus bullonorum Hernando &amp; Castro, sp. nov. head 3 dorsal view 4 lateral view. Head appendages 5 A antennae 5 B maxilar palpi. Elytra and abdomen in dorsal view 6 male 7 female." figureDoi="10.3897/subtbiol.43.83592.figures3-7" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/673888" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">4</figureCitation>
) total length (0.64 mm), maximum width (0.17 mm). Extraordinarily elongate, 3.5 times longer than wide, clearly narrower than pronotum. Frons broadly grooved and distally bilobed, narrow and shallow longitudinal groove starts between both lobes, which extends back to level of eyes. Dorsolateral part with two longitudinal and parallel carinae, clearly higher in supra-ocular area and attenuated backwards, with tomentose fossae very small. Surface entirely microreticulated, dorsal pubescence composed of few short, white, semi-erect setae arranged in pair of lateral longitudinal series. In lateral view (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="33BCCB7F247A214362EF00340B11C251" captionStart="Figures 3–7" captionStartId="F2" captionText="Figures 3 - 7. Geopselaphus bullonorum Hernando &amp; Castro, sp. nov. head 3 dorsal view 4 lateral view. Head appendages 5 A antennae 5 B maxilar palpi. Elytra and abdomen in dorsal view 6 male 7 female." figureDoi="10.3897/subtbiol.43.83592.figures3-7" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/673888" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">4</figureCitation>
), dorsal part practically flat in its anterior part, barely gibbous and slightly narrowed at posterior part. Gular protuberance projecting backward and hook-shaped (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="40A8B328C67902E5CDC7A81125460BDC" captionStart="Figures 3–7" captionStartId="F2" captionText="Figures 3 - 7. Geopselaphus bullonorum Hernando &amp; Castro, sp. nov. head 3 dorsal view 4 lateral view. Head appendages 5 A antennae 5 B maxilar palpi. Elytra and abdomen in dorsal view 6 male 7 female." figureDoi="10.3897/subtbiol.43.83592.figures3-7" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/673888" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">4</figureCitation>
). Tomentose pubescence of ventral part, short and sparse, extending from gular protuberance to basal narrowing (Figs 
<figureCitation id="7669A3C9C9ADDD82060FC7D07DE149FB" captionStart="Figures 8–12" captionStartId="F3" captionText="Figures 8 - 12. Geopselaphus bullonorum Hernando &amp; Castro, sp. nov. Ventral part 8 male 9 female. Aedeagus 10 - 11 dorsal vision 12 lateral vision." figureDoi="10.3897/subtbiol.43.83592.figures8-12" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/673889" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">8</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation id="E3820381CFFE4149B29CD794060B219A" captionStart="Figures 8–12" captionStartId="F3" captionText="Figures 8 - 12. Geopselaphus bullonorum Hernando &amp; Castro, sp. nov. Ventral part 8 male 9 female. Aedeagus 10 - 11 dorsal vision 12 lateral vision." figureDoi="10.3897/subtbiol.43.83592.figures8-12" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/673889" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">9</figureCitation>
). Eyes reduced, with only three unpigmented ommatidia, likely not functional (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="6D92423643B7DA05C3DFD906C5A344A9" captionStart="Figures 3–7" captionStartId="F2" captionText="Figures 3 - 7. Geopselaphus bullonorum Hernando &amp; Castro, sp. nov. head 3 dorsal view 4 lateral view. Head appendages 5 A antennae 5 B maxilar palpi. Elytra and abdomen in dorsal view 6 male 7 female." figureDoi="10.3897/subtbiol.43.83592.figures3-7" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/673888" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">3</figureCitation>
). Antennae (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="0FA92F49C0C03D360CF00178D2A654AD" captionStart="Figures 3–7" captionStartId="F2" captionText="Figures 3 - 7. Geopselaphus bullonorum Hernando &amp; Castro, sp. nov. head 3 dorsal view 4 lateral view. Head appendages 5 A antennae 5 B maxilar palpi. Elytra and abdomen in dorsal view 6 male 7 female." figureDoi="10.3897/subtbiol.43.83592.figures3-7" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/673888" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">5</figureCitation>
) extraordinarily long (1.57 mm) and slender, exceeding the posterior margin of elytra when bent backwards, scape cylindrical and parallel-sided, 3.2 times longer (0.28 mm) than wide (0.04 mm), pedicel cylindrical and subparallel-sided, 1.3 times longer (0.08 mm) than wide (0.04 mm), antennomeres 3-7 cylindrical, equal in length and longer (0.11 mm) than wide (0.04 mm); antennomere 8 cylindrical, with equal width, but shorter (0.06 mm) than previous five; antennomeres 9-10 cylindrical, both very similar in length and shape, wider and twice as long as previous six antennomeres; terminal antennomere very long (0.37 mm) and club-shaped, slightly asymmetrical at apex and with equal length as three previous antennomeres together. Maxillary palps extraordinarily long (1.57 mm) and slender (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="14EFD87F092630C66D8A0EB896E85F47" captionStart="Figures 3–7" captionStartId="F2" captionText="Figures 3 - 7. Geopselaphus bullonorum Hernando &amp; Castro, sp. nov. head 3 dorsal view 4 lateral view. Head appendages 5 A antennae 5 B maxilar palpi. Elytra and abdomen in dorsal view 6 male 7 female." figureDoi="10.3897/subtbiol.43.83592.figures3-7" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/673888" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">5</figureCitation>
), palpomere 1 filiform, slightly curved; palpomere 2 very long (0.48 mm), filiform over practically its entire length and abruptly widened at its apical end; palpomere 3 very short and conical; palpomere 4 very long (0.73 mm), slightly arched, filiform throughout practically its entire length, progressively thickening at apex, which is club-shaped and with surface of thickened part completely covered with granules and very fine and erect pubescence.
</paragraph>
<caption id="AD347C3CBC0AA7A9877D41642F456DBF" doi="10.3897/subtbiol.43.83592.figures3-7" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/673888" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" start="Figures 3–7" startId="F2">
<paragraph id="0D123B18FFD8C99F67FEEC9045DDC61F" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
<emphasis id="AD5B123C06A802E46C52305F8F022152" bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Figures 3-7.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName id="2B37AACB1092DE79FBD39CD4A69E85F8" authorityName="Hernando &amp; Castro" authorityYear="2022" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Geopselaphus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Geopselaphus bullonorum" order="Coleoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="bullonorum">
<emphasis id="F79144517AB333B0ACEE201E95613363" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Geopselaphus bullonorum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Hernando &amp; Castro, sp. nov. head 
<emphasis id="393BB9E4518A22FA95B5882D8956E995" bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">3</emphasis>
dorsal view 
<emphasis id="E43D03FBF059D63A7038EACF5D0C1FEA" bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">4</emphasis>
lateral view. Head appendages 
<emphasis id="95D653E9D4EF06A443F0AC1812BB0ECD" bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">5A</emphasis>
antennae 
<emphasis id="D0E2899CA21FFC8AB22735A848464048" bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">5B</emphasis>
maxilar palpi. Elytra and abdomen in dorsal view 6 male 7 female.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph id="38AB13D32F6693A109D40E927F41C60C" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
<emphasis id="54E727E74328A93DFE528622FBC6D065" bold="true" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Pronotum</emphasis>
: Longer (0.32 mm) than wide (0.24 mm) with subparallel sides, with the anterior and posterior margins straight, the latter finely bordered, surface smooth and shiny and with two dorsal longitudinal series of setae, each consisting of 4-5 white and semi-erect setae.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="45A8678EFAF9025C18BA06A178680E22" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
<emphasis id="00E64CA2C291B92431D11B94B4BA5648" bold="true" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Elytra</emphasis>
: Strongly narrowed at base, practically as long (0.6 mm) as wide (0.62 mm); each elytron with three basal foveae; humeral carinae entire and well-marked, each elytron with raised, entire and well-apparent discal carinae (Figs 
<figureCitation id="54F547354F1F50DA023604FD2F495825" captionStart="Figures 3–7" captionStartId="F2" captionText="Figures 3 - 7. Geopselaphus bullonorum Hernando &amp; Castro, sp. nov. head 3 dorsal view 4 lateral view. Head appendages 5 A antennae 5 B maxilar palpi. Elytra and abdomen in dorsal view 6 male 7 female." figureDoi="10.3897/subtbiol.43.83592.figures3-7" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/673888" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">6</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation id="827727C0709C70437E792CE97DCF9C29" captionStart="Figures 3–7" captionStartId="F2" captionText="Figures 3 - 7. Geopselaphus bullonorum Hernando &amp; Castro, sp. nov. head 3 dorsal view 4 lateral view. Head appendages 5 A antennae 5 B maxilar palpi. Elytra and abdomen in dorsal view 6 male 7 female." figureDoi="10.3897/subtbiol.43.83592.figures3-7" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/673888" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">7</figureCitation>
), with entire sutural stria; surface smooth and shiny, the pubescence on each elytron composed of three series of white and semi-erect setae, two located along the two carinae and a third very short series on the discal surface, with the posterior margins of each elytron decorated by transverse series of semi-erect setae widely spaced and on same edge with dense fringe of tomentose setae (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="76B777AB30F1F4C8C7E10E236A1C7274" captionStart="Figures 3–7" captionStartId="F2" captionText="Figures 3 - 7. Geopselaphus bullonorum Hernando &amp; Castro, sp. nov. head 3 dorsal view 4 lateral view. Head appendages 5 A antennae 5 B maxilar palpi. Elytra and abdomen in dorsal view 6 male 7 female." figureDoi="10.3897/subtbiol.43.83592.figures3-7" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/673888" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">6</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="F7D59E4A4B9DA06CD07416398E8D43E3" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
<emphasis id="96B537B357C63C57DABDACB926F6E659" bold="true" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Ventral part</emphasis>
: Mesoventrite with two very dense clusters of tomentose setae (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="CB271B16D00D2DD5F7FF02EAD13197CF" captionStart="Figures 8–12" captionStartId="F3" captionText="Figures 8 - 12. Geopselaphus bullonorum Hernando &amp; Castro, sp. nov. Ventral part 8 male 9 female. Aedeagus 10 - 11 dorsal vision 12 lateral vision." figureDoi="10.3897/subtbiol.43.83592.figures8-12" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/673889" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">8</figureCitation>
), metaventrite convex, smooth and shiny and with some widely scattered semi-erect setae (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="5878AD3FB6E7DCC1BD16811B8D87F8D3" captionStart="Figures 8–12" captionStartId="F3" captionText="Figures 8 - 12. Geopselaphus bullonorum Hernando &amp; Castro, sp. nov. Ventral part 8 male 9 female. Aedeagus 10 - 11 dorsal vision 12 lateral vision." figureDoi="10.3897/subtbiol.43.83592.figures8-12" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/673889" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">8</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="A053D6D579DD3131EC41F0C5CBC93256" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
<emphasis id="D02CEB6D1BD468407761CBEF0E88204B" bold="true" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Abdomen</emphasis>
: With tergite IV (first visible tergite) very large, clearly wider (0.71 mm) than long (0.51 mm), shorter than the elytra and clearly wider than these, with a smooth and shiny surface and series of semi-erect setae along entire posterior margin. Sternite III (first visible sternite) with a broad transverse fringe of tomentose hairs that occupies entire basal part and with a long tuft of erect setae in central part of posterior margin (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="41EBCD484C164AB2DC52E5347B79AA6C" captionStart="Figures 8–12" captionStartId="F3" captionText="Figures 8 - 12. Geopselaphus bullonorum Hernando &amp; Castro, sp. nov. Ventral part 8 male 9 female. Aedeagus 10 - 11 dorsal vision 12 lateral vision." figureDoi="10.3897/subtbiol.43.83592.figures8-12" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/673889" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">8</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<caption id="5F4060245DFE2B244EEEF83AFB7920F5" doi="10.3897/subtbiol.43.83592.figures8-12" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/673889" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" start="Figures 8–12" startId="F3">
<paragraph id="01C836C7AAE607EAF68739D61FA3981B" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
<emphasis id="E314E4535010640A62D1DBE395C9B9AB" bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Figures 8-12.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName id="CB5D4DC014FEF30DEF3FD66CD15A080E" authorityName="Hernando &amp; Castro" authorityYear="2022" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Geopselaphus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Geopselaphus bullonorum" order="Coleoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="bullonorum">
<emphasis id="232841D3FF8D7C18F4B747EEA32E14F7" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Geopselaphus bullonorum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Hernando &amp; Castro, sp. nov. Ventral part 
<emphasis id="3EF6E64F5E3F16D25AFA9ACF7FCC7935" bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">8</emphasis>
male 
<emphasis id="21A493718C6C86F69B9ABD6040EB88DD" bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">9</emphasis>
female. Aedeagus 
<emphasis id="ACB0B31ABA914E45747739C82226E7A0" bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">10-11</emphasis>
dorsal vision 
<emphasis id="BEDE0A5DEC2B9F6FA48BBA29FDC4DCAF" bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">12</emphasis>
lateral vision.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph id="C7AE186530F1D747CF4CD6CE0AC604FF" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
<emphasis id="56703F749226CA8EFEE40177E09C5260" bold="true" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Male genitalia</emphasis>
: Median lobe strongly acuminate at apex (Figs 
<figureCitation id="FBB1EBF13E23BBF195FC659F52EC9CBB" captionStart="Figures 8–12" captionStartId="F3" captionText="Figures 8 - 12. Geopselaphus bullonorum Hernando &amp; Castro, sp. nov. Ventral part 8 male 9 female. Aedeagus 10 - 11 dorsal vision 12 lateral vision." figureDoi="10.3897/subtbiol.43.83592.figures8-12" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/673889" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">10</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation id="5FEAA3298C8BFBE70FB628A446C234ED" captionStart="Figures 8–12" captionStartId="F3" captionText="Figures 8 - 12. Geopselaphus bullonorum Hernando &amp; Castro, sp. nov. Ventral part 8 male 9 female. Aedeagus 10 - 11 dorsal vision 12 lateral vision." figureDoi="10.3897/subtbiol.43.83592.figures8-12" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/673889" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">11</figureCitation>
) and in lateral view with the apex curved inwards (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="06D3A8C6635CD1141E2175F5732A017A" captionStart="Figures 8–12" captionStartId="F3" captionText="Figures 8 - 12. Geopselaphus bullonorum Hernando &amp; Castro, sp. nov. Ventral part 8 male 9 female. Aedeagus 10 - 11 dorsal vision 12 lateral vision." figureDoi="10.3897/subtbiol.43.83592.figures8-12" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/673889" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">12</figureCitation>
), internal sac with two fascicles of small spines (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="E364D6578CF20A0DB3695BEF463AC5E9" captionStart="Figures 8–12" captionStartId="F3" captionText="Figures 8 - 12. Geopselaphus bullonorum Hernando &amp; Castro, sp. nov. Ventral part 8 male 9 female. Aedeagus 10 - 11 dorsal vision 12 lateral vision." figureDoi="10.3897/subtbiol.43.83592.figures8-12" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/673889" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">11</figureCitation>
) and apical structure formed by modified spines of squamiform shape.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="7F16406ED2AF7C9FDA6379A1CDD77341" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
<emphasis id="80472B47CF6099AD9F73AE1E8782AEF0" bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Female</emphasis>
: General appearance similar to male (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="BE14463296065CD698A30430A6F364FF" captionStart="Figures 1–2" captionStartId="F1" captionText="Figures 1 - 2. Geopselaphus bullonorum Hernando &amp; Castro, sp. nov. Habitus in dorsal view 1 male 2 female." figureDoi="10.3897/subtbiol.43.83592.figures1-2" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/673887" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">2</figureCitation>
), but with posterior margin of the elytra with the fringe of tomentose setae broadest and more developed (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="2D79231A1AA9B7A2DE927512CFAC7F8F" captionStart="Figures 3–7" captionStartId="F2" captionText="Figures 3 - 7. Geopselaphus bullonorum Hernando &amp; Castro, sp. nov. head 3 dorsal view 4 lateral view. Head appendages 5 A antennae 5 B maxilar palpi. Elytra and abdomen in dorsal view 6 male 7 female." figureDoi="10.3897/subtbiol.43.83592.figures3-7" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/673888" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">7</figureCitation>
), tergite IV clearly longer (0.55 mm), practically as long as length of elytra (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="B91E5C01B1ED0E2C21051CF5D8F277B1" captionStart="Figures 3–7" captionStartId="F2" captionText="Figures 3 - 7. Geopselaphus bullonorum Hernando &amp; Castro, sp. nov. head 3 dorsal view 4 lateral view. Head appendages 5 A antennae 5 B maxilar palpi. Elytra and abdomen in dorsal view 6 male 7 female." figureDoi="10.3897/subtbiol.43.83592.figures3-7" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/673888" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">7</figureCitation>
), sternite III longer, without tuft of erect setae and rugulose at the base (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="421E9C3D0B7659A143484470F6D215FD" captionStart="Figures 8–12" captionStartId="F3" captionText="Figures 8 - 12. Geopselaphus bullonorum Hernando &amp; Castro, sp. nov. Ventral part 8 male 9 female. Aedeagus 10 - 11 dorsal vision 12 lateral vision." figureDoi="10.3897/subtbiol.43.83592.figures8-12" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/673889" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">9</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="9DACCFC3C2670AFC95A832208E1D6390" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="comparisons">
<paragraph id="60710EE5FE8DD6DD52A5100B0C8D7E51" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Comparative notes.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="ADE77934A7EC29637FBE50A8596ABD99" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
The new species is well distinguished from the rest of the known species of the genus by its marked troglomorphism, such as the reduction of the eyes (only three unpigmented ommatidia) and an extraordinary general elongation of the body (especially of the head) and appendages (antennae, maxillary palps and legs). It is also characterised by the small size of the tomentose foveae on the head, which are large in the rest of the known species, the elytra have a complete dorsal carina (Figs 
<figureCitation id="0F3816865DD11F5BB2E2E784D66E56A7" captionStart="Figures 3–7" captionStartId="F2" captionText="Figures 3 - 7. Geopselaphus bullonorum Hernando &amp; Castro, sp. nov. head 3 dorsal view 4 lateral view. Head appendages 5 A antennae 5 B maxilar palpi. Elytra and abdomen in dorsal view 6 male 7 female." figureDoi="10.3897/subtbiol.43.83592.figures3-7" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/673888" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">6</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation id="8A3F013DB9A0884386F059EE73C67A82" captionStart="Figures 3–7" captionStartId="F2" captionText="Figures 3 - 7. Geopselaphus bullonorum Hernando &amp; Castro, sp. nov. head 3 dorsal view 4 lateral view. Head appendages 5 A antennae 5 B maxilar palpi. Elytra and abdomen in dorsal view 6 male 7 female." figureDoi="10.3897/subtbiol.43.83592.figures3-7" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/673888" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">7</figureCitation>
), which is absent or slightly elevated in the rest of the known species of the genus, and the aedeagus is quite different (Figs 
<figureCitation id="CEC5915664EEA2DEBAD324310D5BB920" captionStart="Figures 8–12" captionStartId="F3" captionText="Figures 8 - 12. Geopselaphus bullonorum Hernando &amp; Castro, sp. nov. Ventral part 8 male 9 female. Aedeagus 10 - 11 dorsal vision 12 lateral vision." figureDoi="10.3897/subtbiol.43.83592.figures8-12" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/673889" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">10-12</figureCitation>
). It has also been compared with its geographical neighbour 
<taxonomicName id="B690DECFB2C01884FF2C224FFEEFECC8" authorityName="Besuchet" authorityYear="1961" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Geopselaphus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Geopselaphus longulus" order="Coleoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="longulus">
<emphasis id="551AFBDD31BCFC65101B302822D5500B" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Geopselaphus longulus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Besuchet, 1961, an endogean species showing some elongation of the head and palps, but always in comparison with the other endogean species and without any comparison with the new species.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="3E5D1511B771DCF12174A25287DA8600" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
Based on the aedeagus, 
<taxonomicName id="9D9553218B856CB0E481494D0DBF00A1" authorityName="Hernando &amp; Castro" authorityYear="2022" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Geopselaphus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Geopselaphus bullonorum" order="Coleoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="bullonorum">
<emphasis id="6607CE2A7722B55A2DAA10221BB4A21E" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Geopselaphus bullonorum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
seems to be close to 
<taxonomicName id="3840A195C585D41C264A8C5D09872FE3" baseAuthorityName="Coquerel" baseAuthorityYear="1859" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Geopselaphus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Geopselaphus sencieri" order="Coleoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sencieri">
<emphasis id="0923C33DB6B40A2F88D56EFD23C945EE" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Geopselaphus sencieri</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(Coquerel, 1858), distributed in Algeria, Morocco and the extreme south of the Iberian Peninsula (
<bibRefCitation id="8CC39479275819EB257442DE8FD7DDA8" author="Jeannel, R" journalOrPublisher=") (Serie A: Zoologie)" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" pagination="1 - 233" refId="B11" refString="Jeannel, R, 1956. Les Pselaphides de l'Afrique du Nord. Essai de biogeographie berbere. Memoires du Museum National d'Histoire Naturelle, Paris (N. S.) (Serie A: Zoologie) 14: 1 - 233" title="Les Pselaphides de l'Afrique du Nord. Essai de biogeographie berbere. Memoires du Museum National d'Histoire Naturelle, Paris (N. S." volume="14" year="1956">Jeannel 1956</bibRefCitation>
), both species have an acuminate median lobe, and the internal sac is very similar, consisting of two fascicles of spines (see Besuchet 1961).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C4A7DFE9D115B3B95F8D0671C80E2476" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="64CE3D6DCCBC9B3D44B40B8C2CF6F592" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Geographic distribution.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="1541E85E352116B403E03B6513367D0B" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">So far, only known from the typical locality.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="87DF0344A16289931CF48A17CD08CE86" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="habitat">
<paragraph id="C8EB441414A7589AFCA4AB4AE5A9A767" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Habitat.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="FBC972945A727C2FF1819B658BE2FC71" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
The Cueva de la Pileta has a total length of 2.406 m and a maximum slope of 102 m. All the specimens were captured wandering on walls in the sector called &quot;La Gran Sima&quot;, which is in one of the deepest parts of the cave, approximately 400 m from the cave entrance. This cave harbours a rich community of terrestrial subterranean arthropods, 32 species have been recorded so far (
<bibRefCitation id="1830F1A2DF4CF5EFD805CEFC2DFE95FF" author="Perez, T" journalOrPublisher="Gota a gota" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" pagination="58 - 64" refId="B19" refString="Perez, T, Meseguer, A, Bullon, JT, 2013. Aproximacion al estudio de los invertebrados de la Cueva de la Pileta (Benaojan, Malaga, Espana). Gota a gota 3: 58 - 64" title="Aproximacion al estudio de los invertebrados de la Cueva de la Pileta (Benaojan, Malaga, Espana)." volume="3" year="2013">
<normalizedToken id="7D8CA686E838B1394C6CD856F4A4616F" originalValue="Pérez">Perez</normalizedToken>
et al. 2013
</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="C93E303584DE3CC3FCC3829C6CF58031" author="Perez, T" journalOrPublisher="Gota a gota" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" pagination="69 - 70" refId="B20" refString="Perez, T, Aguilera, JM, 2014. Adenda al articulo &quot;Aproximacion al estudio de los invertebrados de la Cueva de la Pileta (Benaojan, Malaga, Espana)&quot;. Gota a gota 3: 69 - 70" title="Adenda al articulo &quot; Aproximacion al estudio de los invertebrados de la Cueva de la Pileta (Benaojan, Malaga, Espana) &quot;." volume="3" year="2014">
<normalizedToken id="DBBB7310C07B6C5060962170F81CBED4" originalValue="Pérez">Perez</normalizedToken>
and Aguilera 2014
</bibRefCitation>
; Miralles and 
<normalizedToken id="DA75D8649A8DDFC8B3931A39D4677938" originalValue="Pérez">Perez</normalizedToken>
2015), of which 12 are exclusively troglobitic. Six of them have a relatively wide distribution: 
<taxonomicName id="51C15EF14C7D58135FA0903452264644" authorityName="Vandel" authorityYear="1952" class="Malacostraca" family="Trichoniscidae" genus="Iberoniscus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Iberoniscus breuili" order="Isopoda" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="breuili">
<emphasis id="8532CB6907C018F6BD0C1549D7A19EC0" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Iberoniscus breuili</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Vandel, 1952, 
<taxonomicName id="A6E388E7B9DD2E93DE3C698B1648A2F7" authorityName="Vandel" authorityYear="1955" class="Malacostraca" family="Trichoniscidae" genus="Trichoniscus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Trichoniscus gordoni" order="Isopoda" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="gordoni">
<emphasis id="C3A364114486C7EC48FA94004C57BB6E" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Trichoniscus gordoni</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Vandel, 1955 (
<taxonomicName id="2D61B777264532409BF9EBC8E86FC01E" authorityName="Brandt" authorityYear="1833" class="Malacostraca" genus="Trichoniscus" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Isopoda" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="order">Isopoda</taxonomicName>
); 
<taxonomicName id="382DA959978FCD804EE445E109C3DE4F" authorityName="Matic" authorityYear="1968" class="Chilopoda" family="Lithobiidae" genus="Lithobius" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Lithobius motasi" order="Lithobiomorpha" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="motasi">
<emphasis id="8E0AB08B8A7F4A3A16DAD83F6BE231ED" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Lithobius motasi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Matic, 1967 (
<taxonomicName id="79A708C6C729D76F1D2B8C2911A0707B" genus="Lithobiomorphae" lsidName="" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="genus">Lithobiomorphae</taxonomicName>
); 
<taxonomicName id="230C022B9DF177EB788DD42EF2ADBD50" authorityName="Fage" authorityYear="1931" class="Arachnida" family="Agelenidae" genus="Tegenaria" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Tegenaria herculea" order="Araneae" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="herculea">
<emphasis id="7B169EE92D11B4EE37B99A32A22D847C" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Tegenaria herculea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Fage, 1931, 
<taxonomicName id="9EEFE0A9F920ADE6FF459F7435ED6FEA" baseAuthorityName="Simon" baseAuthorityYear="1884" class="Arachnida" family="Linyphiidae" genus="Troglohyphantes" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Troglohyphantes furcifer" order="Araneae" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="furcifer">
<emphasis id="51C9B1EAA75418DE4F70B06CD2BB6853" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Troglohyphantes furcifer</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(Simon, 1884) (
<taxonomicName id="9232FE12BBD9233C95E3AC164DCCCF5B" class="Arachnida" genus="Troglohyphantes" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Araneae" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="order">Araneae</taxonomicName>
) and 
